            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Jia Moreno-Goldstein\u2019s name is the first chapter of her San Francisco story. Adopted as an infant from China\u2019s Hunan province, she was raised in the Outer Richmond by her two loving parents: a meticulous Jewish-American architect father and a compassionate Mexican-American social worker mother. Her childhood was a vibrant fusion of cultures\u2014Shabbat dinners one night, homemade tamales the next, and Lunar New Year celebrations in between. Growing up, the city itself was her third parent. Her family didn't own a car, so the rattling Muni bus routes were her window into the city's mosaic of neighborhoods, from the quiet avenues of the Sunset to the bustling energy of the Mission.\n\nThis early, intimate exposure to the city's circulatory system sparked a lifelong fascination. She saw how a reliable bus line could be a lifeline for a family, and how a poorly connected neighborhood could feel like an island. This understanding propelled her to UC Berkeley for her undergraduate studies and subsequently to a graduate program in Urban and Regional Planning, where she specialized in public transportation systems. Her thesis on improving transit equity for elderly and low-income residents in dense urban areas landed her a coveted position as a Transit Planner for the city.\n\nNow 28, Jia lives in a thoughtfully decorated, rent-controlled apartment in the Mission District, a neighborhood that connects her to her mother\u2019s heritage. Her 1.8-mile commute on the 14-Mission bus is a daily field study; she's not just a planner but a user, acutely aware of every delay and every success. Her evenings are spent with a close-knit circle of friends, many of them fellow public servants and urbanists, debating policy over craft beer or exploring new restaurants.\n\nHer dream isn't wealth, but impact. Jia aspires to lead the development of a major Bus Rapid Transit (BRT) project that could reshape mobility for thousands. She feels a profound sense of responsibility to the city that raised her. For Jia, San Francisco is not just a place on a map; it's the complex, frustrating, and beautiful system she was raised within and has dedicated her life to improving, one bus route at a time."
        },
        {
            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "reveries",
            "value": "1.\nJia remembers being seven, her small hand swallowed in her mother\u2019s, watching rain streak the windows of the 38-Geary. An elderly Cantonese woman struggled aboard, her grocery bags dripping. The driver waited patiently, not sighing or rushing. In that quiet moment of communal grace, Jia felt the bus shrinking the city, knitting strangers together. It wasn\u2019t a machine, but a vessel of unspoken care. That feeling\u2014that transit was a form of dignity\u2014lodged deep in her heart and never left.\n\n2.\nShe was thirteen, the year she felt most adrift. It was a Friday night. Her father lit the Shabbat candles, their glow flickering across the kitchen. Simultaneously, the savory steam of her mother\u2019s tamales filled the air. Wax, masa, and blessings mingled. In that moment, her hybrid-identity wasn't a puzzle to solve, but a perfect, warm fusion. She learned that seemingly disparate systems could coexist and create something uniquely wonderful. It was a lesson in beautiful, functional integration.\n\n3.\nDuring her graduate research at Berkeley, she interviewed a man in the Bayview. He described how the infrequent bus service made him feel trapped, like his world had shrunk to three blocks. \"It's a different kind of loneliness,\" he'd said. In his words, Jia heard the echo of her own childhood awe at the city's vastness. It was then her academic pursuit became a moral imperative. She wasn't just studying transit; she was fighting loneliness, one bus route at a time.\n\n4.\nAt 26, her first project was painfully small: a new bus shelter with a bench on a windswept corner in the Sunset. A month after it was installed, she saw three seniors sitting there, chatting while waiting for the 29-Sunset. They were out of the wind, comfortable. It wasn't a new BRT line, but it was real. The victory felt monumental, proving that her plans weren't just lines on a map but tangible acts of care for the city's residents.\n\n5.\nJust last week, riding the 14-Mission home, the bus lurched to a halt. Jia instinctively critiqued the signal timing, even as she felt a deep comfort in the familiar scene: a family speaking Spanish, a student with headphones, an exhausted cook. She was no longer just the child staring out the window; she was the planner who understood the mechanics behind the delay. She felt a profound sense of purpose, realizing she was now a guardian of the very system that had raised her."
